      <div xml:id="NA295-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu tōḻi ceṟippaṟivuṟīi varaivu kaṭāyatu. 2. ciṟaippuṟamumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante urged for marriage by informing of confinement. 2. It is also [when HE is] behind the fence.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA295">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            murinta cilampi ṉerinta vaḷḷiyiṟ</l>
<l>            puṟaṉaḻin tolivarun tāḻiruṅ kūnta</l>
<l>            lāyamu maḻuṅkiṉṟu yāyumaḵ taṟintaṉa</l>
<l>            ḷaruṅkaṭi yayarntaṉaḷ kāppē yentai</l>
<l>            vēṟupaṉ ṉāṭṭuk kāṟara vanta </l>
<l>            palaviṉai nāvāy tōṉṟum peruntuṟaik</l>
<l>            kalimaṭaik kaḷḷiṉ cāṭi yaṉṉavem</l>
<l>            miḷanala miṟkaṭai yoḻiyac</l>
<l>            cēṟum vāḻiyō mutirkam yāmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The companions were upset(?),<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aḻuṅkiṉṟu</term>: here we have a problem of reference, since we would expect a plural, even if <term xml:lang="ta">āyam</term> might be read as a neuter word (i.e. <term xml:lang="ta">aḻuṅkiṉa</term>, as to be found in an ET variant). There is the possibility of splitting and taking <term xml:lang="ta">iṉṟu</term> as parallel form of <term xml:lang="ta">iṉṟi</term> "besides" ("besides the attendants being upset" - thus probably the corrected text given by ET), but the double mark with -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> (<term xml:lang="ta">āyam-um - yāy-um</term>) seems to demand a coordination.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">with [their] hanging dark tresses coming into flourishing,</l>
<l rend="indent2">openly desolate(?)<note place="foot">What is said here about HER playmates? Are they openly showing their distress once they have understood the situation? Or is this an extended description of hair hanging down onto their backs? But what, then, is the point and how to understand the comparison?</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">as the crushed creepers on the curved mountain side,</l>
<l rend="indent4">and mother knew it.</l>
<l>She engaged in guarding with severe protection.</l>
<l>Let us go – may you live – [and] grow old,</l>
<l rend="indent">so that our young beauty stays behind within the house,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as a jar of toddy, noisily drunk(?)</l>
<l rend="indent2">at the big harbour, where the ships with many tasks appear,</l>
<l rend="indent3">come with the wind from many other lands of my father.<note place="foot">The position of <term xml:lang="ta">entai</term> is a little awkward. Probably it is not the lands, but rather the ghat, or here the harbour, of HER father.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
